<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName LSID="2D8175C7-8DB2-50E7-A84D-E0BAFF94F255" authority="C. - I Peng" authorityName="C. - I Peng" authorityYear="2020" class="Cephalopoda" family="Onagraceae" genus="Ludwigia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="glandulosa" status="subsp. nov." subSpecies="brachycarpa">Ludwigia glandulosa Walter subsp. brachycarpa C.-I Peng</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="0" pageNumber="57">subsp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. - I Peng" authorityYear="2020" class="Cephalopoda" family="Graphoceratidae" genus="Ludwigia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="brachycarpa">Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa</taxonomicName>
differs from typical 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. glandulosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="glandulosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">L. glandulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its smaller stature, 10-55(-90) cm (vs. (20-)40-80(-100) cm); narrower leaf blades, 0.3-0.5(-1) cm (vs. 0.3-2.1 cm); shorter sepals, 1.1-1.9 mm (vs. 1.3-2.3 cm); smaller capsules, 2-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.3-2 mm (vs. (4-)5-8(-9) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.6-2(-3) mm); and seed surface cells elongate transversely to length (vs. surface cells elongate parallel to length).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="type material">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Type material.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">USA, Louisiana</emphasis>
, Cameron Parish, 3.2 km W of junction State Highways 82 and 27, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="29" direction="north" minutes="48.62" orientation="latitude" precision="9" value="29.810333">29°48.62'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="93" direction="west" minutes="08.25" orientation="longitude" precision="9" value="-93.1375">93°08.25'W</geoCoordinate>
, 1 m, 16 August 1980, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">C.-I Peng, W. Peng and J. Chen 4367</emphasis>
(holotype: MO 2806683); see fig. 42 in 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" author="Peng, CI" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="221 - 302" refId="B12" refString="Peng, CI, 1989. The systematics and evolution of Ludwigia sect. Microcarpium (Onagraceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76 (1): 221 - 302, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" title="The systematics and evolution of Ludwigia sect. Microcarpium (Onagraceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" volume="76" year="1989">Peng (1989)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Stems</emphasis>
rarely reddish green, 10-55(-90) cm. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Leaves</emphasis>
: petiole 0-1 cm, blades linear-elliptic to linear, sometimes very narrowly elliptic, those on main axis 3-5(-7) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.5(-1) cm, those on branches 0.8-3.6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2-0.3(-0.8) cm. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Inflorescences</emphasis>
: bracteoles attached at base of ovary, 0.4-0.8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.1-0.2 mm. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Flowers</emphasis>
: sepals 1.1-1.9 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-1.8 mm, apex acute or short-acuminate; nectary disc obscurely, minutely papillose; style 0.4-0.8 mm, stigma 0.2-0.3 mm diam. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Capsules</emphasis>
obscurely 4-angled, 2-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.3-2 mm, pedicel 0-0.2 mm. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Seeds</emphasis>
0.6-0.8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.4 mm, surface cells elongate transversely to seed length. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Chromosome number</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">n</emphasis>
= 16.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Flowering and fruiting April to November.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
The subspecific epithet ' 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">brachycarpum</emphasis>
' refers to the short capsules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. - I Peng" authorityYear="2020" class="Cephalopoda" family="Graphoceratidae" genus="Ludwigia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="brachycarpa">Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa</taxonomicName>
is endemic to the US Gulf Coast from southwestern Louisiana to Nueces County, Texas, and more sporadically northward in eastern Texas to south-central Oklahoma. This distribution is at the extreme southwestern edge of that for subsp. 
<taxonomicName class="Cephalopoda" family="Graphoceratidae" genus="Ludwigia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="subsp. glandulosum" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="glandulosum">glandulosum</taxonomicName>
, which grows from Texas and Oklahoma east to Virginia and Florida and north to southern Missouri, Illinois, and Indiana (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" author="Peng, CI" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="221 - 302" refId="B12" refString="Peng, CI, 1989. The systematics and evolution of Ludwigia sect. Microcarpium (Onagraceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76 (1): 221 - 302, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" title="The systematics and evolution of Ludwigia sect. Microcarpium (Onagraceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2399348" volume="76" year="1989">Peng 1989</bibRefCitation>
). Although they overlap in part, the two taxa are only rarely locally sympatric. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. - I Peng" authorityYear="2020" class="Cephalopoda" family="Graphoceratidae" genus="Ludwigia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="brachycarpa">Ludwigia glandulosa subsp. brachycarpa</taxonomicName>
grows in ditches, low meadows, coastal prairies, seeps in sandy woods, moist sinkholes in granite outcrops, old clay fields at an elevation of 0-200 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="new combinations">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">New combinations</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Epilobium" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Epilobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. is the largest genus in the family 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Onagraceae</taxonomicName>
; its 165 species are widely distributed in cool or cold regions of the world, with a center of diversity in western North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Wagner, WL" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="1 - 240" refId="B16" refString="Wagner, WL, Hoch, PC, Raven, PH, 2007. Revised classification of the Onagraceae. Systematic Botany Monographs 83: 1 - 240" title="Revised classification of the Onagraceae." volume="83" year="2007">Wagner et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
). A group of annual species with affinities to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Epilobium" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Epilobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but considered distinct because they lack seed comas was historically segregated as 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Boisduvalia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Boisduvalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Boisduvalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Spach (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395311" author="Raven, PH" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="326 - 340" refId="B14" refString="Raven, PH, 1976. Generic and sectional delimitation in Onagraceae, tribe Epilobieae. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 63 (2): 326 - 340, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2395311" title="Generic and sectional delimitation in Onagraceae, tribe Epilobieae." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395311" volume="63" year="1976">Raven 1976</bibRefCitation>
). However, molecular and other evidence (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16727" author="Hoch, PC" journalOrPublisher="Phytologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="456 - 459" refId="B5" refString="Hoch, PC, Raven, PH, 1992. Boisduvalia, a coma-less Epilobium (Onagraceae). Phytologia 73: 456 - 459, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16727" title="Boisduvalia, a coma-less Epilobium (Onagraceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.part.16727" volume="73" year="1992">Hoch and Raven 1992</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2419763" author="Baum, DA" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="363 - 388" refId="B1" refString="Baum, DA, Sytsma, KJ, Hoch, PC, 1994. The phylogeny of Epilobium (Onagraceae) based on nuclear ribosomal DNA sequences. Systematic Botany 19 (3): 363 - 388, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2419763" title="The phylogeny of Epilobium (Onagraceae) based on nuclear ribosomal DNA sequences." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2419763" volume="19" year="1994">Baum et al. 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wagner, WL" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="1 - 240" refId="B16" refString="Wagner, WL, Hoch, PC, Raven, PH, 2007. Revised classification of the Onagraceae. Systematic Botany Monographs 83: 1 - 240" title="Revised classification of the Onagraceae." volume="83" year="2007">Wagner et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
) unequivocally place 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Boisduvalia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Boisduvalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Boisduvalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
within 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Epilobium" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Epilobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as two non-monophyletic sections. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoch &amp; Gandhi" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Hoch &amp; Gandhi" baseAuthorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Epilobium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Epilobium subsp. sect." order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Epilobiopsis" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="sect.">Epilobium sect. Epilobiopsis</taxonomicName>
(Spegazzini) Lievens, Hoch &amp; PH Raven is a group of two species characterized by tough, tardily dehiscing capsules, seeds in two rows per locule, and a chromosome number of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">n</emphasis>
= 15; and 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. subsp. sect." pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="section" section="Boisduvalia" species="glandulosa" subSpecies="sect.">E. sect. Boisduvalia</taxonomicName>
(Spach) Hoch &amp; P. H. Raven is a group of four species characterized by friable, readily dehiscing capsules, seeds in one row per locule, and chromosome numbers of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">n</emphasis>
= 9, 10, 19. In naming this latter section, however, we overlooked an earlier name at the sectional level, one of two proposed for this group by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fischer, FEL" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" refId="B3" refString="Fischer, FEL, Meyer, CA, 1836. Index Seminum [St. Petersburg (Petropolitanus)] 2: 45." title="Index Seminum [St. Petersburg (Petropolitanus)] 2: 45." year="1836">Fischer and Meyer (1836)</bibRefCitation>
, who treated the group as part of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Oenothera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Oenothera" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Oenothera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. due to the absence of seed comas. Therefore, a new combination is required.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
